BOTULISM ADVISORY - CANADA, USA: BACKGROUND
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Botulism advisory - Canada, USA 990115114529
Date: Sun, 17 Jan 1999 08:11:00 +0200
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on botulism in Canada were extracted from the
GIDEON software program:
- 106 cases were reported during 1981 to 1990 (32 in 1985 and 26 in 1987).
- 9 cases were reported in 1991 (6 of these from the Northwest Territories,
for a rate of 11/100,000 population).
- 9 cases were reported in 1992. Three cases were reported in 1993, and 3
in 1994 (from the Northwest Territories).
- Seven outbreaks (16 cases - none fatal) and one case of infant botulism
were reported in 1995 - implicated foods included muktuk, micerak
(fermented fat of marine mammals), seal, walrus and marinated/smoked fish.
- 14 cases were reported in 1996 (10 of these from Quebec) Five outbreaks
of foodborne botulism (10 patients - no fatalities) were reported in 1996 -
implicated foods included seal, fermented fish, beluga whale and micerak.

- 5 cases were reported in 1997 (all from the Northwest Territories). Two
outbreaks were reported in August 1997: one (Northwest Territories)
involved 4 cases (one fatal); the second (a family in northern Quebec)
involved a family who had eaten seal meat - no fatalities.
- 2 cases were reported during the first half of 1998.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
e-mail: mberger@post.tau.ac.il
